  "prompt": "Which one is better: the American Dream or the American dream? Dream with a capital letter or not?",
  "response": "The distinction between \"American Dream\" with a capital \"D\" and \"American dream\" with a lowercase \"d\" is more a matter of stylistic choice than a question of one being better than the other. \n\nThe term \"American Dream\" is often capitalized to denote it as a specific cultural concept or ideal. This usage typically refers to the aspirational belief in the United States that anyone, regardless of their background, can achieve success and upward mobility through hard work and determination.\n\nOn the other hand, \"American dream\" with a lowercase \"d\" might be used in a more general sense or when discussing individual variations of the concept that don't necessarily align with the broader, traditional understanding. \n\nThe choice between the two depends on the context in which you are writing or speaking and whether you want to emphasize the notion as a recognized, collective idea. Neither option is inherently better, as the capitalization is mostly about clarity and emphasis.",
